    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Waterfront Park for Brooklyn?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jeff Prant letter, commenting on August 16 article, opposes construction of waterfront park in Brooklyn Heights</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The primary problem posed by the current design for Brooklyn Bridge Park (news article, Aug. 16) is not that the surrounding neighborhood will be overwhelmed by pedestrians. The more profound impact will likely be huge increases in car traffic because of a design that actively encourages auto use.</p>
        <p>Within its 70 acres, 1,500 parking spaces are currently planned. This is in stark contrast to Central Park (850 acres and no public parking) and Prospect Park (525 acres and 300 spaces).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The primary problem posed by the current design for Brooklyn Bridge Park (news article, Aug. 16) is not that the surrounding neighborhood will be overwhelmed by pedestrians. The more profound impact will likely be huge increases in car traffic because of a design that actively encourages auto use.</p>
        <p>Within its 70 acres, 1,500 parking spaces are currently planned. This is in stark contrast to Central Park (850 acres and no public parking) and Prospect Park (525 acres and 300 spaces).</p>
        <p>In an area with excellent public transit and pedestrian access, this reflects an outdated suburban-style mentality that promotes driving as a primary means of traveling to the park.</p>
        <p>JEFF PRANT  Brooklyn, Aug. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
